article.headline: USC 90, UC Irvine 70
article.story: LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Gabe Pruitt and Dwayne Shackleford gave Southern California a glimpse of a promising season in their debuts. Pruitt became the first true freshman in the last 10 years to lead the team in scoring in a season-opener with 13 points and USC defeated UC Irvine 90-70 Monday night. Shackleford, a junior-college transfer from Washington D.C., added 12 points. Together, Pruitt and Shackleford combined to shoot 71 percent from the floor and 50 percent from 3-point range. "To start, I was jittery," said Pruitt, who came from Westchester High in Los Angeles. "I could've played better, but it'll come." Shackleford rallied the Trojans late in the first half when they trailed by seven points. All seven of USC's field goals over the final 12:49 of the half were 3-pointers, including three each by Errick Craven and Shackleford. His last one left them trailing 37-36 at the break. "It was a big boost," Pruitt said of Shackleford. "He brought the energy out and kept it up. We kind of fed off it." Shackleford wasn't expected to play because he is still rehabilitating from left knee surgery in mid-October. "But coach gave me the look and it was time to check in," he said, smiling. With Irvine starters Ross Schraeder and Greg Ethington in foul trouble, the Trojans opened the second half with a 33-15 run to take a 69-52 lead. It was their first lead since 6:50 of the opening half. "We had a chance to capitalize in the first half, but what really hurt was Greg Ethington picking up his third foul," Irvine coach Pat Douglass said. "He's our only experienced post player and it was a blow." Aaron Fitzgerald scored a career-high 24 points to lead the Anteaters (1-1), who had a 1-11 road record last season. Schraeder added 15 points. "In the second half, we just kind of slowed everything down and maybe took them for granted," Fitzgerald said. "Greg being out hurt us too. We got a hand up on the shots, they just hit a lot of good shots." During USC's run, Shackleford slipped a nifty behind-the-back pass to Pruitt, who scored. Later, Pruitt converted off a teammate's miss and scored on a fast-break layin. Pruitt had three assists and three steals to go with one turnover. "His performance was excellent," USC coach Henry Bibby said of Pruitt. "He responded very well. He's a smooth player and he's very heady. We think he can get better." Errick Craven also had 13 points -- one of six Trojans in double figures for the first time since the 2003 Pac-10 tournament against Oregon. Jeff McMillan added 12 points and 12 rebounds. Lodrick Stewart had 11 and Derrick Craven 10. Errick Craven's lone steal gave him 204, tying Jeff Trepagnier for third on USC's career list. The Trojans improved to 7-2 in season openers under Bibby, starting his ninth season. They are 4-1 against the Anteaters, who were playing USC for the first time since 1997. Irvine is 9-26 all-time against Pac-10 teams. Pruitt and freshman Nick Young were on the floor at the same time. Young's 3-pointer capped the scoring for USC.
